## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| **Critical** | 6 |
| **Medium** | 2 |
| **Low** | 1 |

This is a textbook **coverage-touching** test class. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is invoked (achieving line coverage), but almost nothing is actually verified. These tests will pass even if the implementation is completely broken — explaining bugs in production despite 95% coverage.

---

### 🔴 Critical — False Confidence

#### 1. Coverage-Touching (Systemic)

The entire class follows the pattern: call a method, assert nothing (or only `IsNotNull`). 6 of 10 tests have **zero assertions**; the remaining 4 use only `Assert.IsNotNull` which verifies nothing meaningful.

---

#### 2. No Assertions — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17–21)

```csharp
// BEFORE — proves nothing
_catalog.AddProduct(product);

// AFTER — verify the product was actually stored
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var stored = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", stored?.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, stored?.Price);
```

#### 3. No Assertions — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32–36)

```csharp
// BEFORE — never checks the price changed
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);

// AFTER
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated!.Price);
```

#### 4. No Assertions — `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 39–43)

```csharp
// BEFORE — never verifies removal
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");

// AFTER
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
```

#### 5. No Assertions — `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63–66)

```csharp
// BEFORE — doesn't even capture meaningful state
var count = _catalog.GetProductCount();

// AFTER
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
Assert.AreEqual(1, _catalog.GetProductCount());
```

#### 6. No Assertions — `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 69–74)

This is the most dangerous: a 10% discount is applied but never verified. A bug in the discount math ships silently.

```csharp
// BEFORE
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);

// AFTER
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(8.991m, updated!.Price);  // 9.99 * 0.90
```

#### 7. Trivial `IsNotNull` — `GetProduct_Works`, `SearchProducts_Works`, `GetAllProducts_Works`, `ExportToCsv_Works`

`Assert.IsNotNull` only proves the method didn't return `null`. It doesn't verify correctness.

```csharp
// BEFORE (SearchProducts_Works, line 50–51)
var results = _catalog.Search("Widget");
Assert.IsNotNull(results);

// AFTER — verify the search actually found the right product
var results = _catalog.Search("Widget");
Assert.AreEqual(1, results.Count);
Assert.AreEqual("SKU-001", results[0].Sku);
```

